= El CNH se disuelve

MÉXICO, D.F., diciembre de 1968 —

On the sixth of December the Consejo Nacional de Huelga votes itself out of existence, in a hall with more empty chairs than delegates. Half its leadership is in Lecumberri. One of its most famous voices, Sócrates Campos Lemus, named names for the cameras within days of his arrest — reading from a script whose author everyone can guess, but the doubt he planted works exactly as designed: every surviving assembly now conducts its business while wondering who else is rehearsed.

The strike is over. The schools reopen under watch, informers thick in the front rows. And two hundred thousand students who spent a summer learning things no Mexican university teaches — how to run a press, how to hold an assembly that actually votes, how to speak to a bus full of strangers, how to outrun a granadero — are dispersing with the knowledge still warm in their hands.

Some will go home and become the sensible men their fathers wanted. A few take the scholarships that appear, suddenly and generously, for study abroad. Some are asking, warily, about the Party — warily, because they remember July, when the Party told them to be prudent. And some, the ones with dead friends and steady hands, have begun to speak very quietly about geography: about Guerrero, about Chihuahua, about what a man named Gámiz tried at Madera three years ago, on a date some of them have started using as a signature.

- @reclutar: Open the doors wide. Youth sections, brigades, presses — let the comités walk in as comités, banners and bad discipline and all.
- @filtrar: Recruit carefully, one by one. Half these assemblies have a DFS informer taking minutes, and Campos Lemus proved it.

@reclutar
choose-if: sup_students >= 35
unavailable-subtitle: The comités will not walk through a door they do not respect. (Requires student support.)
