They come in with their own songs, their own martyrs, and their own perfect contempt for your hierarchies — nineteen-year-olds who correct the Central Committee's Spanish and win the argument. The old cadres' meetings will never be quiet again, and some of the old cadres quietly begin to miss the silence.

But the Party is alive in a way it has not been since the forties: presses running, dues arriving in coins, a youth section that needs restraining rather than reviving. Somewhere in Bucareli, a filing cabinet gets a new drawer, and a clerk types your organization's name at the top of a fresh index.

@filtrar
on-arrival: cnh_recruited = 2; members += 1; sup_students -= 3; guerrilla_meter += 5; expediente += 3

Careful, correct, cold. Each candidate vouched for by two members, each biography checked against the arrest lists, the Campos Lemus lesson applied with surgical rigor. The informers find the door shut; so does almost everyone else.

The ones you turn away do not stop being angry; they take the anger elsewhere. A boy from the Poli — nineteen, a good speaker, a brother beaten half to death on the second of October — shakes your organizer's hand politely, thanks the Party for its time, and goes to look for people less careful. Years from now, someone will read his name in a newspaper and remember this afternoon.
